\begin{theorem} 
\label{thm:MovingSumOfFractions}
	For all integers $n\geq2$,
	$$
		\sum_{k=1}^n\frac{1}{n+k} \geq \frac{7}{12}.
	$$
\end{theorem}


\begin{proof}

We will prove theorem 2 by induction on n. Firstly, let us look at the base case $n = 2$.

$$\sum_{k=1}^2\frac{1}{2+k} \geq \frac{7}{12} $$
$$\Leftrightarrow \frac{1}{2+1}+\frac{1}{2+2} \geq \frac{7}{12} $$
$$\Leftrightarrow \frac{1}{3}+\frac{1}{4} \geq \frac{7}{12} $$
$$\Leftrightarrow \frac{4+3}{12} \geq \frac{7}{12} $$
$$\Leftrightarrow \frac{7}{12} \geq \frac{7}{12}. $$

$P(n)$ is true for $n = 2$. Now, assuming that the theorem holds for some integer $n$, let us have a look at $P(n+ 1)$:

$$\sum_{k=1}^{n+1}\frac{1}{n+1+k} $$

For the theorem to hold, this summation will also have to be greater than or equal to $\frac{7}{12}.$.

We already know that $P(n) \geq \frac{7}{12}$ for $n = 2$. If we can prove that $P(n+1) \geq P(n) $, then we will know that $P(n+1)$ is also greater than or equal to $\frac{7}{12}$. 

Therefore, let us test the inequality below. We will call it lemma 1.

$$\sum_{k=1}^{n+1}\frac{1}{n+1+k} \geq \sum_{k=1}^{n}\frac{1}{n+k}. $$

Expanding the sums for a few terms, we have:

$$\frac{1}{n+2} + \frac{1}{n+3} + \cdots + \frac{1}{2n+1}+ \frac{1}{2n + 2} \geq \frac{1}{n+1} + \frac{1}{n+2} + \cdots + \frac{1}{2n}.$$

Cancelling the repeating terms and subsequently rearranging the inequality, we have:

$$\frac{1}{2n+1} + \frac{1}{2n+2} \geq \frac{1}{n+1} $$
$$\Leftrightarrow \frac{1}{2n+1} + \left(\frac{1}{2} \times \frac{1}{n+1}\right) \geq \frac{1}{n+1} $$
$$\Leftrightarrow \frac{1}{2n+1}  \geq \frac{1}{n+1} - \left(\frac{1}{2} \times \frac{1}{n+1}\right) $$
$$\Leftrightarrow \frac{1}{2n+1}  \geq \left(\frac{1}{2} \times \frac{1}{n+1}\right) $$
$$\Leftrightarrow \frac{1}{2n+1}  \geq \frac{1}{2n+2} $$
$$\Leftrightarrow 2n + 2 \geq 2n + 1 $$
$$\Leftrightarrow 2 \geq 1 .$$

Two is greater than one, so lemma 1 holds. In other words, $P(n+1) \geq P(n) $. Since we have already shown that $P(n) \geq \frac{7}{12}$ for $n = 2$, lemma 1 implies, by transitive law, that $P(n+1) \geq \frac{7}{12}$. Theorem 1 therefore holds.


\end{proof}

